1 Introduction
Programmers traditionally rely on strong consistency to preserve data integrity. Strong consis-
tency masks the intricacies of transaction execution over distributed data with unpredictable
communication delays and concurrency, but sacrifices runtime performance [15]. Weaker consis-
tency mechanisms offer higher performance but can cause application-level integrity violations if
used naively [4, 71]. This is exacerbated by the fact that for some applications, in addition to the
CAP tradeoff [29], programmers might need to trade off consistency and latency [2]. If integrity
requirements are too strict, programmers often have no option but to sacrifice performance so
that consistency fulfills the integrity requirements of their applications for the worst case [68].1
Moreover, the required consistency levels are tied to the semantics of particular operations and
distribution aspects, and any change to either of the two has to propagate changes in the consis-
tency model through a costly development cycle [40, 72, 77, 86]. Automating this choice in such
1This follows from the impossibility of achieving atomic consistency and availability [29]. The lesser-known PACELC
theorem argues a fundamental trade-off between latency and consistency exists even without partitions/failures [2].
