119:2 Ivan Kuraj, John Feser, Nadia Polikarpova, and Armando Solar-Lezama
a setting, and the subsequent implementation, while attaining high-level integrity provided by
strong consistency, remains a challenge.
Prior work has proposed using static analysis to identify when operations are allowed to execute
under weak consistency to optimize performance for a large class of applications [4, 30, 36, 37, 40, 68].
However, the employed static analyses are conservative, as they have to account for the potential
worst-case that might occur at run time. In this paper, we present an automated approach that uses
symbolic reasoning over executions of a bounded number of operations to derive efficient checks
that attempt to weaken the reordering of concurrent operations at run-time. Our approach provides
two key advantages over the purely static approach. First, we can exploit fine-grained optimization
opportunities that only occur in specific situations at run time. Existing techniques must revert
to strong consistency whenever an interleaving of operations that violates integrity exists, even
when those operations are not invoked together at runtime. Second, the verification burden of
our approach is smaller than other approaches that must verify that the chosen consistency level
maintains integrity for all possible inputs and unbounded interleavings. Instead, our approach
checks that integrity is maintained for bounded executions and uses this information and the
dynamic information obtained from the run-time checks to perform optimization safely and
profitably.
To better facilitate our consistency optimization strategy, we introduce batch-based consistency,
which defines a specialized consistency model given a set of semantic properties. Batch-based
consistency is parameterized over two kinds of application-specific integrity properties—safety
and congruence—and generates a specialized consistency model that restricts the system’s states. A
safety property must be held in every state. A congruence property must be restored periodically
after a finite number of state changes. (Extending the property of replicas converging to the same
state used in prior work [36, 68].) Programmers specify the desired level of consistency by specifying
the two kinds of integrity properties, picking a point between eventual and strong consistency. This
allows programmers to limit the discrepancy of states between nodes at any point and weakens the
strict notion of state convergence (all nodes have to see the effects of distributed operations in the
same order as if a sequential execution produced the effects), introducing opportunities for relaxing
orderings of operations at run time. Consistency optimization can then optimize consistency at
run time, as long as the execution maintains the specified integrity properties.
Batch-based consistency optimization.We implement our approach (batch-based consistency
optimization) in the Peepco tool. Peepco takes the definition of a sequential object, data allocation
specification, and integrity properties defined as predicates on the object state, and synthesizes
a message-passing implementation that respects the allocation specification and executes object
methods as distributed operations. Peepco infers consistency requirements from the specification
and allocates data, splits and allocates computation, and integrates the results into our new run-time
protocol, to implement the batch-based consistency model with the specified integrity.
Our approach relies on a statically constructed oracle that determines if an operation can safely
execute given dynamic information about the operations running in the distributed system. Our
strategy relies on the insight that if we have such an oracle, we can use standard techniques
for distributed agreement [31] to relax consistency. (Such techniques implement the consensus
abstraction, which allows nodes to propose and agree on values.) Once all nodes agree on the
operations that can be executed concurrently, they can be executed in any order the oracle deems
safe. The oracle is then used to implement batched execution: given the set of operations in a batch,
a new operation is allowed to execute in the batch only if: 1) the oracle allows it to run concurrently,
and 2) it follows execution order concerning other operations in the batch, as specified by the
oracle.
Proc. ACM Program. Lang., Vol. 9, No. OOPSLA1, Article 119. Publication date: April 2025.
Peepco: Batch-Based Consistency Optimization 119:3
The strategy uses a new run-time distributed algorithm—PeepCommit—which operates in batches
and uses the oracle to add as many non-conflicting operations to a batch as possible, falling back
to strong consistency when the batch might contain conflicting operations. We present both a
blocking and a non-blocking protocol that implement the strategy, where the latter supports
resiliency to node crashes at a performance cost. All nodes in the system consult the same oracle
locally while maintaining safety and restoring congruence at the end of each batch. The correctness
and performance of the strategy directly depend on the set of relaxed orderings known to the
oracle. To construct the oracle, we introduce integrity-driven consistency strengthening, a new SMT-
based bounded symbolic analysis algorithm for consistency inference for batch-based consistency.
The algorithm discovers the consistency requirements of bounded execution traces of operations
derived from sequential objects at compile time. Our algorithm is efficient; it incrementally builds a
set of consistency requirements and uses them to aggressively prune the set of execution traces
to explore, in addition to using traditional symmetry-breaking techniques. The efficient analysis
allows us to explore traces up to nontrivial bounds, even when the integrity invariants allow
many operation reorderings. While the bounded nature of our analysis means that it can miss
optimization opportunities, it will not lead to unsound executions.
In addition to full replication (where all nodes replicate the application state), we extend our
approach to support partial replication, where some parts of the application data are split among
nodes and others are replicated [11]. Partial replication is often a requirement for modern dis-
tributed applications, which rely on sharding and fine-grained allocation on the backend to achieve
security and performance [72]. It also enables “local-first” applications on the front end [41]. Partial
replication introduces new opportunities for optimization, which Peepco can take advantage of.
Target applications. Not all applications can benefit from our approach. For a large class of
applications that can satisfy integrity with weak consistency, Peepco will pay an unnecessary
performance penalty when running its coordination-based protocol, as shown in § 6. We show how
Peepco’s static analysis results can suggest to programmers to try using weak consistency ([68])
and avoid penalties if possible (§ 3).
However, the border around the mentioned class is thin. For example, consider the well-studied
bank account example [36, 68] with a replicated balance that prevents overdrafts. The example
admits weak consistency optimizations. As deposits and withdrawals commute, delivering them
in any order will ensure that replicas converge to the same local balance. Withdrawals cannot be
executed concurrently, to prevent overdraft, but deposits can be freely interleaved with either of
the two operations, as they increase the balance: this can bring significant speedups [68]. However,
if an interest operation is introduced, which increases the balance based on a given percentage, the
application no longer admits weak consistency optimization. Namely, executing deposits can no
longer proceed to freely interleave, as they do not commute with interest. For such cases, a static
analysis must conservatively resort to strong consistency for all involved operations to prevent bad
reorderings. However, if interest operations are rare (likely), often only deposits and withdrawals
will be executed concurrently, for which reordering is allowed. Peepco exploits such cases, by
detecting and allowing reordering at run time.
As causal consistency often remains one of the strongest consistency models that remain avail-
able during system partitions [5], optimizing consistency for such applications remains a challenge,
leaving developers with no option but to forego latency, to satisfy the integrity, of their applica-
tions [2]. These applications are the focus of our approach: Peepco pays for the cost of coordination
that might be nevertheless hard to avoid, but still relaxes concurrency and orderings of operations
to improve performance based on the dynamic information across nodes at run time.
Limitations. Prior work has demonstrated optimization in the space of a wide variety of
consistency notions [37, 73]. Similarly to prior work [22, 36, 49–51], however, we limit our work to
