3.3 Consistency Constraints and Lattice
Peepco implements CanBatchI , required by batch-based consistency, by identifying bad traces
and inferring requirements on the order of operations that would prevent those traces. We follow
prior work [37, 68] and characterize the space of consistency models as a finite lattice, defined
over standard notions of visibility and program order between executed operations, where the
partial order denotes the relative strength of the models [68, 78]. We define a consistency constraint
to be a predicate 𝑐 (𝑡1, 𝑡2) on traces that holds on valid orderings of operations of types 𝑡1, 𝑡2. A
consistency constraint is represented by a tuple of two operation types 𝑡1, 𝑡2 and a consistency
level 𝑙 , which we write as 𝑙 (𝑡1, 𝑡2). Peepco supports three consistency levels 𝐿𝑏 : weak, causal,
and strong, but adding a new level is straightforward (and we do so in § 4.1). Each element of
the lattice is a set of constraints C. We define a “weaker than” relation ⊏ between consistency
constraints: for any operation types 𝑡1, 𝑡2,𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑘 (𝑡1, 𝑡2) ⊏ 𝑐𝑎𝑢𝑠𝑎𝑙 (𝑡1, 𝑡2) ⊏ 𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑔(𝑡1, 𝑡2). Predicates
are not symmetric: e.g., 𝑐𝑎𝑢𝑠𝑎𝑙 (𝑎, 𝑏) says that 𝑎 needs to observe a causally preceding 𝑏. (They
describe the rules of delivery of 𝑎 with respect to deliveries of 𝑏.) For any set of levels 𝐿, 𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑔
(total order) and𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑘 (free reordering) are the greatest and least elements in 𝐿, respectively. We
extend ⊏ to sets of constraints: C1 ⊏ C2 if ∀𝑒1 ∈ C1 . ∃𝑒2 ∈ C2 . 𝑒1 ⊏ 𝑒2. In our example, the set
{𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑔(withdrawal, deposit)} prevents the given violation, but it is not the weakest that does
so, as the causal ordering {𝑐𝑎𝑢𝑠𝑎𝑙 (withdrawal, deposit)} prevents it as well and is weaker with
respect to ⊏. Peepco reports if an operation 𝑜 does not conflict with any other,  ′ ′𝑜 . 𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑔(𝑜, 𝑜 ),
suggesting to programmers that 𝑜 might admit weak consistency.
A trace 𝜏 satisfies constraints C (in other words, C holds for 𝜏) if the order of execution of
operations in 𝜏 does not violate the ordering prescribed by consistency levels of all constraints
𝑐 ∈ C. For example, in Fig. 6, for the given trace 𝜏 , {𝑤𝑒𝑎𝑘 (withdrawal, deposit)} holds on 𝜏 , but
{𝑐𝑎𝑢𝑠𝑎𝑙 (withdrawal, deposit)} does not.
