Next, we define the notion of optimality of consistency choices in the given model. We say that
C is optimal if: 1) there is no correct C′ such that C′ ⊏ C, or 2) C = C′ ⊔ C′′ if both C′ and C′′
are optimal. We enforce the second condition to allow choosing a single element of the lattice as
the solution (otherwise in the context of multiple optimal solutions, unrelated by ⊏, exist). In all
of our benchmarks, as well as most practical programs, there is no ambiguity in terms of optimal
solutions. (We characterize optimality in the context of batch-based consistency and a more general
notion of optimality in Appendix B.)
