Only if the opposite does not hold, i.e., 𝜏𝑒 is feasible under C
′, C′ gets removed. Merge then returns
a new solution C𝑏 which is the least upper bound of the remaining constraints. Importantly, for
any C′ that is filtered out, all the traces that were pruned based on C′ (line 5) in the current 𝑏 or
any bound before 𝑏, are re-explored in Ω𝑏 (as they might still contain undiscovered, but needed,
constraints).
The pruning strategy achieved by Merge allows supporting non-inductive invariants (regardless
of the monotonicity of I), as constraints discovered in a bound 𝑏 might restrict traces within
smaller bounds ′𝑏 < 𝑏. This goes beyond approaches that rely on inductiveness [36], but does not
pose an issue for “enumerate-and-check” approaches [37].
Correctness. For well-formed and monotonic invariants, Infer is: sound—if it returns a solution,
it admits only traces that satisfy integrity; complete—if a solution exists, Infer will return it;
optimal—the returned solution is the weakest.
Proof. Soundness holds due to the fact that all traces are either checked or pruned, based on
the least upper bound of the weakest elements that prevent all found violating traces. In case a
constraint is filtered out with Merge, all the pruned traces will be re-scheduled for exploration.
As the algorithm checks all traces, for well-formed invariants at least strong consistency will
be returned. Optimality relies on the fact that the algorithm correctly identifies the weakest set
of constraints that prevent individual traces (line 12), merges them with ⊔, and prunes traces
that would be infeasible under those constraints. Due to monotonicity, the orderings that caused
consistency violations cannot be made viable by adding new operations, thus the solution for larger
bounds cannot be made weaker. We present the full proof in the extended version of the paper. □
Note that for a non-monotonic program, Infer is sound but not necessarily optimal. We discuss
monotonicity and provide a simple example of non-monotonicity in Appendix C.
4 Extensions
In this section, we extend our approach for partial replication to allow data to be distributed across
nodes [11], as well as a non-blocking protocol for fault tolerance.
4.1 Partial Replication
We consider how developers can leverage partial replication to allocate data to specific nodes,
and leverage additional consistency optimization opportunities. We characterize semantics and
implementation details of partial replication in Appendix A.
