Specifications.We introduce an extended banking application that restricts the amount that can
be withdrawn and tracks the last withdrawal (Fig. 7). We modify withdraw to check if the amount
is within the limit max and add a method set that updates max as a percentage of bal. Fig. 8 shows
a possible data allocation and is achieved with the specification shown in Fig. 9. We declare three
node sets, 𝑁𝑟 (replicas), 𝑁𝑐 (clients), and 𝑁ℎ (storage), and specify the data distribution. bal is
replicated on 𝑁𝑟 . Each client node in 𝑁𝑐 gets its copy of last and max. (Clients, e.g., ATMs, show
the last transaction, similarly to a realistic bank interface, which shows the last few transactions
after the user logs in.) The distribute keyword copies the given variable across the given node set.
hist is allocated to the single node of 𝑁ℎ .
4 allocate, behaves similarly to distribute, but restricts
allocation to a single node, so 𝑁ℎ must be a singleton set. We adapt our existing integrity properties
for the new data allocation and add a safety property (i3): the last withdrawal should not be
greater than max on all clients 𝑁𝑐 . (We later describe executions that violate i3.)
Distributed execution. The key change to distributed execution is that methods access fields
that are only stored on certain nodes, so Peepco splits them (based on operation semantics and data
allocation) into actions that execute on the node where the needed data is located. These actions
have control-flow dependencies on other actions belonging to the same method. For example,
withdraw is split into actions that have control flow dependencies as shown in Fig. 10, where
𝑛 : 𝑎 shows action 𝑎 executed on 5𝑛 . Actions represent indivisible units of computation and reflect
the sequential semantics of the method they belong to. While programmers write operations as
atomic pieces of code that access data spread across different nodes, Peepco automatically handles
operation splitting that dictates distributed execution, as well as, potentially, consistency choices
at run-time. We define the semantics of execution under partial replication, as well as effects on
consistency optimization, in Appendix A.
For example, consider method calls withdraw(80) and set(50), and their execution, shown
in Fig. 8. Invocations of ′ ′withdraw comprise five actions: 𝑤𝑠 ,𝑤𝑏,𝑤 ,𝑤𝑙 and 𝑤ℎ , where 𝑤 is an
