Protocol. In full replication, any conflicting method can be dispatched to any node; in partial
replication, some nodes never get a conflicting action. Peepco takes advantage of that fact to
minimize consensus invocations. Peepco statically infers (a concrete set of nodes 𝑁 ) two disjoint
sets of nodes for a given program: consensus nodes 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 and non-consensus nodes 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 (where
𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 = 𝑁 \ 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 ). The 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 nodes must include any node on which a conflicting action executes.
Non-consensus nodes do not participate in consensus and only listen for decisions from consensus
nodes. In our example, only withdraw has a conflicting action:𝑤𝑏 , which executes on 𝑁𝑟 = {𝑛1, 𝑛2}.
This labeling and derived constraints, where the ones bolded force the 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 label, is shown in Fig. 11
(considering set and deposit, where abbreviated method names designate the only method action
on that node). As other methods are also dispatched on 𝑁𝑟 (and their first actions modify state), we
let 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 = 𝑁𝑟 (shown with a dotted line in Fig. 12).
We depict an execution of the extended protocol in Fig. 12, where solid dots represent action
execution and empty dots represent protocol events. Nodes in 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 exchange votes as before
(message {pr}). They agree on batches and notify 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 , when: 1) a method is accepted into a batch
and propagates next actions (dashed, unlabeled, lines in Fig. 12; line𝑄5 of Alg. 1), and 2) the batch is
finalized, with a new message {fin} (dashed lines). Here,𝑤𝑏 invokes the consensus. After accepting
𝑤𝑏 into the batch, 𝑛1 informs 𝑛ℎ and 𝑛𝑐 that their actions can be executed.
Non-consensus nodes can progress if they know which batch they are in and actions carry the
batch number of their methods. When a non-consensus node receives an action belonging to the
batch the node is in, it executes the action in the order prescribed by the oracle. If the batch numbers
do not match, the node waits to process the action until it catches up. 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 nodes obtain information
about methods that are accepted in the batch, as well when the batch is closed from 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 , so they
can safely determine which batch they are in. In our example, 𝑛ℎ receives the control message {fin}
after executing𝑤ℎ . After executing an action, the node checks if it executed all actions of methods
in the current batch and can proceed to the next batch (similarly as in line 𝐹2 of Alg. 1). As {fin}
confirmed that withdraw is the only accepted method, 𝑛ℎ proceeds to the next batch.
Peepco executes read-only actions that precede conflicting actions without invoking consensus.
Here,𝑤𝑠 is read-only: it performs the check and spawns𝑤𝑏 , which invokes consensus.𝑤𝑠 , however,
constrains the order of set calls, as shown below.
In general, methods may have: 1) multiple conflicting actions and 2) actions preceding conflicting
ones that modify the state. Actions in either of the groups cannot avoid consensus. To handle the
general case, Peepco infers sets of actions, per method, that need to go through consensus (akin
to transaction chains [14, 87]) and sets 𝑁𝑐𝑛𝑠 accordingly. We present the extended protocol in the
extended version of the paper.
Inference. Inferring consistency constraints for actions is largely the same as for methods. In our
example, the effects of withdraw and deposit actions on replicas 𝑁𝑟 have the same consistency
requirements as before, in the granularity of actions. For example, strong(𝑤 ,𝑤 ) designates
