predecessors of the action (in the program order), and node on which action executes, respectively.
The depicted trace 𝜏 does not satisfy 𝑑𝑒𝑙𝑎𝑦, i.e., 𝜏 ̸ |=𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑠 𝑑𝑒𝑙𝑎𝑦 (𝑎1, 𝑎2). A constraint 𝑑𝑒𝑙𝑎𝑦 (𝑎1, 𝑎2)
effectively prevents executing 𝑎1 on 𝑛 if any predecessor of 𝑎2 already executed on 𝑛. (𝑑𝑒𝑙𝑎𝑦 is
weaker than 𝑠𝑡𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑔, but incomparable to 𝑐𝑎𝑢𝑠𝑎𝑙 ; we will characterize the extended consistency
lattice in the extended version of the paper.) Here, the constraint forces a delay on set, locally on
𝑛𝑐 , until all𝑤𝑙 s of pending withdraws finish or are aborted (locking the node locally). This allows
Peepco to batch the two together.
Correctness.We show that these changes achieve B(I)-consistency and preserve the correctness
properties of Infer and PeepCommit in the extended version of the paper.
4.2 Non-blocking Protocol
In this section, we present the non-blocking version of PeepCommit, FTPeepCommit. If a quorum
(majority) of nodes is correct, every method call will eventually get a response while
B(I)-consistency is maintained.
Key idea. The crux of FTPeepCommit remains the same as 𝑛1
in PeepCommit, where voting is used to determine if a new
operation can be added to the current batch. We add another [vote] [commit]
phase that happens after voting, in which FTPeepCommit at- 𝑛2
tempts to collect confirmations about the decision to add a new [pre-commit]{pr}
operation (borrowing the idea from quorum-based commit 𝑛3
[69]). Once FTPeepCommit receives enough confirmations,
it then proceeds to disseminate the decision. The additional Fig. 15. FTPeepCommit
phase allows the protocol to tolerate failures even of the node
Proc. ACM Program. Lang., Vol. 9, No. OOPSLA1, Article 119. Publication date: April 2025.
Peepco: Batch-Based Consistency Optimization 119:19
that initiated the voting: in case of at most 𝑓 failures, where 𝑁 = 2𝑓 + 1, at least one node that
knows about the outcome, i.e., final decision, will remain non-faulty (responsive).
Protocol.Wedescribe the protocol extensions, needed to achieve a new phase, called “pre-commit”
(dotted lines), as shown in Fig. 15. Phases “vote” and “commit” are the same as in PeepCommit (in
case of a successful call). Requests (lines 𝐶1−2 in Alg. 1), proposals (𝑃1−7), and voting, up to the
decision part (𝑄1−4) are re-used in FTPeepCommit. Instead of initiating execution on “all-yes” (𝑄5−6),
the initiating node 𝑛 in FTPeepCommit broadcasts a “pre-commit” message to all participants, for
the given operation. On receiving the message, participants confirm the witnessing of the decision
to add the operation to the batch. (If 𝑛 is believed to be faulty, e.g., after a timeout, participants will
deny the pre-commit attempts from 𝑛, causing the abort behavior.) When 𝑛 collects confirmations
from at least a quorum of all nodes (|𝑁 |/2 + 1), 𝑛 initiates the execution (as in𝑄5−6), and the rest of
the actions mimic those in PeepCommit (𝑅1–𝑆3).
While we described a successful, no-fault scenario, FTPeepCommit still aborts if any of the
processes vote “no” in either “vote” or “pre-commit” phases (these messages are shown with dashed
lines in Fig. 15). In case of faults, the protocol enters a “recovery phase” to elect a new transactor,
which Peepco adopts from [69]. We provide the full protocol in the extended version of the paper.
5 Implementation
Peepco is implemented in approximately 29k lines of Scala (22k for static analysis and 7k for
the runtime). We use Leon’s [42] Scala frontend (which includes lexing and parsing) and Leon’s
verification conditions for data structures with recursive predicates.We use Z3 [21] to discharge SMT
queries. Peepco’s networking stack is implemented using Akka [1] (on top of TCP-based channels).
The input to Peepco is a Scala source file containing a set of functions and data constructors, along
with the integrity and data distribution specifications.
Inference.We implement Infer (Alg. 2) as a parallel worklist procedure and incorporate addi-
tional strategies for pruning into Choose:
• Effect-driven pruning examines variable reads and writes to prune traces that cannot change the
invariants [28].
• Symmetry breaking avoids reordering identical effects from calls of the same method [24].
In addition, our exploration engine includes several optimizations aimed at rewriting and simplifying
symbolic values before invoking the external solver. We provide additional details in Appendix E.
Protocol. PeepCommit can exhibit starvation when there are repeated aborts. To remedy this
Peepco employs a strategy for breaking ties during voting that favors calls with many retries, as
well as with fewer conflicts according to CanBatchI .
Safe and congruent reads. Peepco, by default, executes node-local reads as safe, and multi-node
reads as congruent. Peepco implements congruent reads by executing them at the end of the current
batch, collecting the state from all the needed nodes.
6 Evaluation
In this section, we evaluate our implementation and illustrate the performance benefits of consis-
tency optimization in batch-based consistency. We also evaluate Peepco’s sensitivity to different
workloads and the impacts of the explored bound at run-time.
Inference benchmarks.We consider the following CRDTs and replicated applications introduced
in prior work: LWWRegister [65]: a last-write-wins register, where reads return the value of the latest
write; NNCounter [36]: a non-negative counter with increment and decrement; Bank account [68]:
our motivating example; Courseware [30]: a database model for course enrollments; Microblog [37]:
