require strong consistency. Peepco uses the inference results after 15 minutes of search (reported in
Table 1). We measured throughput (Fig. 17) on the Bank use case, fully replicated on 8 cluster nodes.
Throughput is measured as operations completed per second. We performed three experiments. In
the first experiment, Bank(w,d,i), uniform (Fig. 17a), clients choose one of the four methods (three
write methods, and a safe read) uniformly. Peepco achieves significantly more throughput than
Classify—over 2.2× for 64 clients on each node. Peepco allows non-conflicting method calls at run
time to proceed concurrently, which are assigned strong consistency by Classify and need to invoke
2PC in the worst case. Going through a round-trip communication to ensure total order in the worst
case is expensive, and fast reads do not alleviate the issue. We also run the same experiment, on
Bank(w,d), uniform (Fig. 17b). (This is equivalent to the motivating example examined in [36, 68].)
Classify outperforms Peepco and demonstrates better scalability, as deposits are executed without
requiring an agreement phase and potential rollback due to conflicts in other operations in the
batch, as well as its size. In our third experiment, Bank(w,d,i), skewed (Fig. 17c), we only require
congruence, and clients invoke interest only 5% of the time (and withdraw and deposit 35%).
Peepco’s speedup increases to 2.6× because the only method that requires total order (interest) is
present infrequently causing fewer aborts when the other two methods are invoked.
We examined response times on Courseware, deployed in the same way. We measure the time
between issuing the method call and receiving a response of success and report the average, across
all requests made (Fig. 17d). The 6 bars in the figure designate the number of clients per node.
Peepco’s response time is significantly lower than that of the strong consistency baseline. The
read-only method query has the lowest response time because it does not require a round-trip.
The other methods have significantly higher response times, with delCourse dominating because
it conflicts with addCourse and enrol, each of which has only one pairwise conflict. We also
measure throughput for Courseware (Fig. 17e) and find that it is higher than for Bank (∼1.5×
speedup improvement, for 960 clients), due to the lower number of conflicts, relative to the executed
operations in the uniform workload.
