7 Related Work
Static analysis for consistency optimization. The idea of using static analysis to optimize
consistency was motivated by a line of work. Quelea [68] introduced static analysis for consistency
optimization, using high-level contracts. Q9 [37] added application-specific invariants and pro-
posed the use of bounded symbolic reasoning. Hamsaz [36] extended the idea with the synthesis of
replicated objects, and Hampa [52] added reasoning about recency. ECROs [22] avoid coordination
further by local reordering. Atropos [63] introduced consistency optimization by exploring adjust-
ments in the program’s data layout. Peepco combines static reasoning with runtime information to
realize new optimization opportunities, while allowing specializing consistency model through
integrity, and, in turn controlling and exposing state after convergence, periodically. Peepco’s
protocol, however, is blocking and requires agreement even for non-conflicting operations. In
addition to replicated objects, Peepco extends the expressiveness to support partial replication.
Run-time techniques. Sieve [49, 50] defines a consistency model called RedBlue which executes
operations with two modes of consistency. Olisipo [51], refines the approach and presents two
coordination protocols, where one can be used for infrequent operations. Peepco supports static
analysis in the extended consistency lattice, including weak consistency, automatically checks
that integrity holds, and uses dynamic information to allow concurrent execution of operations.
Warranties [53] and “treaties” in Homestasis [64], presented the idea of using run-time checks for the
node-local state that allows avoiding coordination. By contrast, Peepco’s run time checks optimize
operations even when a treaty might be violated, as they are informed by using global dynamic
information, collected from other nodes in the system, through the new protocol. Moreover, Peepco
additionally supports protocols such as causality and delays, as well as congruence properties.
Elaborate specifications. Some approaches let developers aid the consistency optimization
by providing, tags and conflicts between tags CISE [30, 60], counterexample fixes for inductive
generalizations [61], and conflict avoidance annotations in Indigo [8, 10], conflict resolutions in
IPA [9] and consistency guards in Carol [48]. By contrast, Peepco provides automation while only
requiring the specification of high-level invariants. While Peepco cannot provide the guarantees
of unbounded full verification ([47, 59, 79]), empirical evidence suggests it provides performance
benefits by leveraging results from a relatively expressive SMT-based bounded-reasoning procedure,
while preserving application-specific integrity at run time.
Type systems. Disciplined inconsistency [35] presents a type system that disallows the flow of
weakly consistent values into strongly consistent operations unless allowed by the programmer.
MixT [57] introduced transactional support with types that allow accessing different stores with
varying consistency guarantees and used information flow analysis to limit the influence of weakly
consistent data on transaction control flow. Some programming models allow mixing consistency
levels to some extent [23, 35, 43, 80]. Peepco splits methods into pieces under data partitioning,
but it does not require consistency annotations to be associated with objects and locations, and it
infers the consistency of each piece automatically. Peepco, moreover, assigns consistency levels to
particular operation splits, rather than fixing a particular object or memory location with a specific
model. It considers control-flow dependent splits, as well as other operations that might occur at
run-time, but it does not handle loops.
Replicated objects. Replicated objects and data types have been proposed [16, 65, 66, 83, 84],
studied in terms of invariant preservation [3, 4, 54], and used in systems [7, 86]. MRDTs [40]
have shown that such objects allow deriving merge functions that can alleviate conflicts and
provide safety. Quark [39] then introduced convergence with run-time assistance, and Peepul [70]
verifies their efficient implementations. Katara [45] used lightweight ordering constraints. The
space of consistency models has been characterized in terms of a partially-ordered lattice [73, 78].
Proc. ACM Program. Lang., Vol. 9, No. OOPSLA1, Article 119. Publication date: April 2025.
Peepco: Batch-Based Consistency Optimization 119:25
PRACTI [11] motivated the partial replication model and defined flexible consistency as one of its
key components. Peepco follows the approach of encoding different consistency levels as a lattice.
Peepco, however, also supports partial replication by extending reasoning about the system to
many different nodes and includes the flexibility of programmer-specialized consistency models, in
addition to being “tunable” based on the operation semantics [78].
Databases and transactional systems. Prior work has studied correctness conditions for find-
ing the lowest isolation level for transactions [27, 55]. Alone-Together [38] formulated a program
logic for automated verification of weakly-isolated transactions. In addition, transaction decompo-
sition was used to aid such reasoning, with transaction chopping [18, 67], step-decomposition [13],
transaction chains [87], locality-aware [19] and security-aware decomposition [85]. Other work
incorporates run-time heuristics into chopping approaches, to extract concurrency [58, 81, 87].
Similarly, Peepco splits methods, treating them as transactions. However, Peepco employs a new
bounded exploration procedure that it uses to achieve automated run-time classification and avoid
the pitfalls of limited information analysis of traditional chopping.
Some approaches for transaction management, such as Calvin [75], Coco [56] and other deter-
ministic databases [25, 26] amortize the cost of the coordination protocols by running transactions
deterministically across multiple nodes and introduce epochs in which multiple transactions can
batch together. While some of these systems need to know a transaction’s read/write set, to prevent
conflicting accesses, or rely on optimistic checks that might abort transactions, one distinguishing
feature of Peepco is that it analyzes the semantic properties of operations (and invariants) so that it
can dynamically start different operations concurrently (e.g. an operation is accepted into the batch
while other are currently running). While these systems usually leverage some a priori known
criteria for fixing the operations in the batch, such as a common cutoff time (e.g. 10 ms), Peepco
does this dynamically and might decide to close the batch early or late, depending on the given
workload.
Context-dependent consistency. There is significant prior work on reducing coordination with
context-dependent techniques: by allowing (bounded) staleness in replicas [6, 82], by providing
applications with a choice between fast inconsistent results and slower consistent results [32], or by
dynamically tuning consistency in response to load [44, 74]. In contrast to these approaches, Peepco
does not reduce coordination but attempts to increase concurrency through batching, according to
the dynamic context. Peepco, however, provides fast local reads, as well as congruent snapshots
that do not slow the system down, regardless of conflicts in the update methods.
8 Conclusion
Our approach explores a new point in the consistency optimization design space, by combining static
analysis results with dynamic communicated information obtained at run time. It allows optimizing
applications that do not admit weak consistency, nor eventuality, where the coordination cost is
likely inevitable. Our strategy allows a specialized consistency model based on the application’s
needs and provides access to congruent snapshots that do not delay other operations. Our approach
supports both replication and distribution, providing a higher degree of optimization when static
analysis runs longer. We implemented our approach in Peepco, which includes a front-end DSL,
a code synthesizer, and a JVM-based run-time. Our evaluation shows the approach can bring
significant performance benefits over the state-of-the-art, especially in cases where operations
might conflict only with relatively few other operations or their parts.
